1
00:00:11,699 --> 00:00:17,239
Richard Guida grew up in the tiny sheep and crop farming town of Tamberlup, 290 kilometres

2
00:00:17,239 --> 00:00:21,500
south-east of Perth, from remote country Western Australia.

3
00:00:21,719 --> 00:00:25,600
Richard's life of leadership and success in corporate Australia is a remarkable story.

4
00:00:26,039 --> 00:00:32,520
From 2005 to 2017, Richard was CEO and Managing Director of Wesfarmers, Australia's largest

5
00:00:32,520 --> 00:00:33,380
private employer.

6
00:00:33,939 --> 00:00:38,280
He's currently the Chairman of listed companies Qantas, Woodside Petroleum, Chairman of the

7
00:00:38,280 --> 00:00:44,200
AFL, WA Symphony Orchestra, the Channel 7 Telethon Trust, the Juvenile Diabetes Research

8
00:00:44,200 --> 00:00:49,700
Fund Australia, and former Chair of Australia's B20, a key business advisory to the World

9
00:00:49,700 --> 00:00:54,340
Economic Forum, which includes business leaders from all G20 economies.

10
00:00:54,719 --> 00:00:56,259
Richard, that's a lot on your plate.

11
00:00:56,320 --> 00:00:57,039
It's great to see you.

12
00:00:57,060 --> 00:00:57,939
Thanks for taking the time today.

13
00:00:58,140 --> 00:00:59,000
Great to be with you, Luke.

14
00:00:59,179 --> 00:01:00,780
Appreciate you doing that.

15
00:01:00,780 --> 00:01:06,439
I look at your story of leadership and how you've been in some of the most high-profile

16
00:01:06,439 --> 00:01:08,260
leadership roles in Australian public life.

17
00:01:08,280 --> 00:01:14,799
And from a small sheep farming town in country WA, can you share with us, what do you think

18
00:01:14,799 --> 00:01:18,159
are the traits that have enabled you to be in those positions?

19
00:01:19,040 --> 00:01:21,659
A bit of luck on the way, Luke.

20
00:01:22,400 --> 00:01:26,560
I actually think growing up in the country was a wonderful upbringing.

21
00:01:28,400 --> 00:01:33,819
Mum and Dad were the best farmers in the world, but I saw drought, I saw poor commodity prices,

22
00:01:33,819 --> 00:01:37,939
I saw external factors impacting.

23
00:01:38,280 --> 00:01:41,060
And it built a bit of resilience, I think.

24
00:01:41,099 --> 00:01:43,819
It built a bit of self-reliance.

25
00:01:44,739 --> 00:01:47,219
And so I think that's helped on my journey.

26
00:01:47,859 --> 00:01:54,120
It also actually gave me an ambition not to be a farmer, because I saw that life was challenging

27
00:01:54,120 --> 00:01:54,939
for Mum and Dad.

28
00:01:54,939 --> 00:02:02,760
So I've always been ambitious, still am ambitious, to do things to make change, hopefully for

29
00:02:02,760 --> 00:02:03,200
the better.

30
00:02:05,000 --> 00:02:06,939
And I mentioned life.

31
00:02:08,280 --> 00:02:10,379
But I've had some luck along the way.

32
00:02:10,460 --> 00:02:10,780
I was lucky.

33
00:02:10,919 --> 00:02:14,080
I got a great education at boarding school in Perth.

34
00:02:14,800 --> 00:02:19,120
I was lucky enough to be a Rotary Exchange student way back in 1978 in upstate New York,

35
00:02:19,120 --> 00:02:25,400
and that was important for me in terms of looking at capitalist society, if you like,

36
00:02:25,419 --> 00:02:25,960
in the US.

37
00:02:26,699 --> 00:02:28,520
I had a great tertiary education.

38
00:02:28,520 --> 00:02:33,979
And when I left university, there were more jobs than there were graduates.

39
00:02:34,639 --> 00:02:36,900
So I was able to have a lot of fun at uni.

40
00:02:37,000 --> 00:02:38,259
I met my wife at university.

41
00:02:38,280 --> 00:02:48,439
But I've always been driven, but hopefully with a sense of balance, but a pretty clear

42
00:02:48,439 --> 00:02:49,520
idea of where I wanted to get to.

43
00:02:49,840 --> 00:02:55,199
So that sort of ambition, Richard, at a young age, as you said, great life experiences and

44
00:02:55,199 --> 00:02:59,979
great education, but did you have that focus to get to these sort of roles?

45
00:03:00,199 --> 00:03:05,180
I was silly enough when I was young to tell my friends that I wanted to be Prime Minister

46
00:03:05,180 --> 00:03:08,259
one day, which they continually remind me of.

47
00:03:08,520 --> 00:03:10,319
Thank God for Australia, that never happened.

48
00:03:11,120 --> 00:03:17,699
So yeah, I sort of always wanted to be in a position where I could be a decision maker.

49
00:03:18,520 --> 00:03:20,099
And I love that.

50
00:03:20,199 --> 00:03:24,139
I love being in a position where you make decisions.

51
00:03:25,219 --> 00:03:27,879
Now, the reality is you get some right, you get some wrong.

52
00:03:29,199 --> 00:03:31,020
When you get them right, it's fantastic.

53
00:03:31,099 --> 00:03:33,020
When you get them wrong, you get your head whacked.

54
00:03:33,020 --> 00:03:37,939
But I sort of rather be that than sitting in the background.

55
00:03:38,259 --> 00:03:39,819
Not being that decision maker.

56
00:03:40,159 --> 00:03:42,879
Well, you become CEO of West Farmers 2005.

57
00:03:43,360 --> 00:03:48,520
Speaking of making decisions, it's only two years into your term that you acquire Coles.

58
00:03:48,580 --> 00:03:50,500
It's a $20 billion takeover.

59
00:03:50,639 --> 00:03:54,199
And I think, Richard, correct me if I'm wrong, that's still the biggest corporate takeover

60
00:03:54,199 --> 00:03:54,919
in Australian history.

61
00:03:55,080 --> 00:03:55,819
Is that still the case?

62
00:03:55,840 --> 00:03:56,460
It was at the time.

63
00:03:56,520 --> 00:03:57,819
Probably not now, Luke.

64
00:03:57,919 --> 00:04:02,240
But what was interesting about that from a leadership point of view is, you're right,

65
00:04:02,240 --> 00:04:03,539
I took over in 2005.

66
00:04:03,539 --> 00:04:06,419
In 2006, we had an opportunity to acquire a business.

67
00:04:07,520 --> 00:04:08,159
And I sort of had this...

68
00:04:08,259 --> 00:04:13,039
It's a bit of a naive view on leadership at the time, which was everyone in the team

69
00:04:13,039 --> 00:04:14,719
will march together shoulder to shoulder.

70
00:04:15,780 --> 00:04:19,839
And I sort of worked out through that period that actually leaders have to lead.

71
00:04:20,220 --> 00:04:29,019
And I made a couple of bad calls during that potential acquisition in 2006 because I wasn't

72
00:04:29,019 --> 00:04:29,779
prepared to lead.

73
00:04:29,779 --> 00:04:32,879
I was hoping that everyone would be lockstep.

74
00:04:33,680 --> 00:04:38,000
And so I sort of learned in 2006 that actually as a leader, you have to lead.

75
00:04:38,259 --> 00:04:47,339
So when the Coles opportunity came along in 2007, I sort of determined to myself that

76
00:04:47,339 --> 00:04:48,199
I was going to lead this.

77
00:04:48,319 --> 00:04:49,439
And I was going to...

78
00:04:49,439 --> 00:04:53,639
I basically put everything else aside and got to work on it.

79
00:04:54,180 --> 00:05:00,740
And that was, I think, significant in how we were able to navigate our way through,

80
00:05:00,740 --> 00:05:05,879
which was a very complex time because the first waves of the global financial crisis

81
00:05:05,879 --> 00:05:07,639
started coming through in 2007.

82
00:05:07,639 --> 00:05:10,339
It was a big acquisition for West Farmers.

83
00:05:11,560 --> 00:05:17,860
But what I'd sort of learned in the preceding years helped drive that outcome.

84
00:05:17,860 --> 00:05:20,399
And it was an amazing year.

85
00:05:21,019 --> 00:05:25,740
And following 10 years that I was CEO, it transformed West Farmers.

86
00:05:26,259 --> 00:05:30,899
And Richard, it's interesting to hear you talk about having that chance in 2006, wanting

87
00:05:30,899 --> 00:05:34,680
to get everyone to march with you and talking to a lot of different leaders from different

88
00:05:34,680 --> 00:05:35,040
backgrounds.

89
00:05:35,319 --> 00:05:36,860
We generally feel there's a shift.

90
00:05:36,860 --> 00:05:41,879
There's a shift away from the old school hierarchical leadership into a more collaborative

91
00:05:41,879 --> 00:05:42,500
approach.

92
00:05:42,620 --> 00:05:46,759
We're sitting at the AFL house here this morning, and you look at the senior AFL coaches are

93
00:05:46,759 --> 00:05:50,699
much more collaborative than the predecessors in the past.

94
00:05:50,839 --> 00:05:53,860
But you just said really clearly then, leaders need to lead.

95
00:05:54,079 --> 00:05:56,819
How do you see the change in leadership now?

96
00:05:57,319 --> 00:06:01,540
Well, look, I think it's incredibly important when you're leading an organisation to have

97
00:06:01,540 --> 00:06:03,540
really good people around you.

98
00:06:03,540 --> 00:06:06,819
And it's a real challenge when you've been a peer of those people.

99
00:06:06,819 --> 00:06:09,980
And then you're elevated to be the leader.

100
00:06:11,160 --> 00:06:16,079
And because your expectations and standards or mine certainly changed.

101
00:06:17,300 --> 00:06:19,660
But so I think that's really important.

102
00:06:19,720 --> 00:06:24,959
And having good, diverse voices, whether it's a board, whether it's a management team, is

103
00:06:24,959 --> 00:06:25,319
important.

104
00:06:25,519 --> 00:06:31,079
And more often than not, as a leader, I got great information and the decision was already

105
00:06:31,079 --> 00:06:31,459
made.

106
00:06:32,100 --> 00:06:36,199
But there are times when it's a hard decision.

107
00:06:36,819 --> 00:06:41,000
Often with people, they're really hard decisions or it's a hard, you know, we're going to do

108
00:06:41,000 --> 00:06:43,819
something and we're prepared to put ourselves out to make it.

109
00:06:44,019 --> 00:06:46,319
And that's when I think leaders have to lead.

110
00:06:47,060 --> 00:06:53,800
And I'll often say that to young people, you know, it's definitional in the word, leadership.

111
00:06:54,060 --> 00:06:54,939
You have to lead.

112
00:06:55,000 --> 00:06:58,939
So I would not describe myself as autocratic, far from it.

113
00:06:59,680 --> 00:07:02,779
You know, I'd certainly describe myself as a team player.

114
00:07:02,779 --> 00:07:05,500
I think you're right about coaches.

115
00:07:05,600 --> 00:07:06,699
I think you're right about leaders.

116
00:07:06,819 --> 00:07:07,120
Generally.

117
00:07:07,399 --> 00:07:12,220
But I still think the best leaders in their own way lead.

118
00:07:12,300 --> 00:07:14,279
And I look at Mandela.

119
00:07:14,759 --> 00:07:19,860
I look at people like Gail Kelly, who I think was a phenomenal corporate leader in Australia.

120
00:07:20,439 --> 00:07:26,600
I look at some of the political leaders who have made a big difference and can look back

121
00:07:26,600 --> 00:07:28,720
on their term and say, we got things done.

122
00:07:28,720 --> 00:07:33,139
And it's because they were prepared to be held accountable for making decisions that

123
00:07:33,139 --> 00:07:34,379
they led on.

124
00:07:34,639 --> 00:07:36,720
So you think the balance is there where you can...

125
00:07:36,819 --> 00:07:37,939
You can still give everyone a voice.

126
00:07:38,060 --> 00:07:39,019
You can still listen to people.

127
00:07:39,079 --> 00:07:39,779
You can still be collaborative.

128
00:07:40,060 --> 00:07:40,199
Yeah.

129
00:07:40,459 --> 00:07:44,399
But ultimately, if a hard call comes, you need to own it as a leader.

130
00:07:44,519 --> 00:07:44,980
Is that...?

131
00:07:44,980 --> 00:07:45,139
Yeah.

132
00:07:45,300 --> 00:07:45,459
Yeah.

133
00:07:45,779 --> 00:07:48,860
And so I'll try and give a reasonably quick example.

134
00:07:48,959 --> 00:07:53,579
During Coles, as I said, the first ripples of the global financial crisis started coming

135
00:07:53,579 --> 00:07:53,879
through.

136
00:07:53,959 --> 00:07:56,600
And that changed what we were planning to do.

137
00:07:56,600 --> 00:08:03,120
We were planning to do a joint venture with private equity to acquire a number of the

138
00:08:03,120 --> 00:08:06,600
businesses in the Coles group, including Coles and the...

139
00:08:06,819 --> 00:08:08,040
Supermarket and Coles Liquor.

140
00:08:08,040 --> 00:08:17,120
And then their ability to fund it fell away because of tightening of liquidity.

141
00:08:17,339 --> 00:08:18,899
The private equity groups bought out?

142
00:08:19,060 --> 00:08:19,160
Yeah.

143
00:08:19,620 --> 00:08:24,819
So I went for a run, plod, in Perth.

144
00:08:26,060 --> 00:08:31,420
And I came back and I asked one of our guys to run some numbers on what it would look

145
00:08:31,420 --> 00:08:33,320
like if we're doing it on our own.

146
00:08:35,019 --> 00:08:36,759
And unsurprisingly, the numbers were good.

147
00:08:36,820 --> 00:08:41,019
Because the debt that Westfarmers could source was cheaper than the debt that private equity

148
00:08:41,019 --> 00:08:42,279
partners could source.

149
00:08:43,159 --> 00:08:46,700
And so I went to the board the next day and said, I think we should still do this.

150
00:08:47,200 --> 00:08:49,019
And here's what the numbers look like.

151
00:08:50,220 --> 00:08:53,000
And that was the brave call, if you like.

152
00:08:53,220 --> 00:08:54,080
There were two brave calls.

153
00:08:54,080 --> 00:08:59,139
One was to spend a couple of billion dollars buying equity in Coles and that early on.

154
00:08:59,320 --> 00:09:01,779
And then going ahead on our own.

155
00:09:02,440 --> 00:09:04,059
Because we could have pulled back at that stage.

156
00:09:04,559 --> 00:09:05,980
But I'm glad we didn't.

157
00:09:06,820 --> 00:09:09,259
So sometimes you've just got to make a call.

158
00:09:10,379 --> 00:09:14,000
And when they work out like that, it's probably a career-defining moment in lots of ways.

159
00:09:14,000 --> 00:09:15,240
It goes the other way.

160
00:09:15,539 --> 00:09:19,559
You're probably not sitting here in a lot of different roles, potentially, which is...

161
00:09:19,559 --> 00:09:20,000
100%.

162
00:09:20,000 --> 00:09:25,620
My wife, Janine, said to me, because there was a lot of media on all this, and early

163
00:09:25,620 --> 00:09:26,779
on there were lots of doubts.

164
00:09:26,840 --> 00:09:27,879
There's always doubters.

165
00:09:28,059 --> 00:09:30,679
And you know that from where you are now on everything.

166
00:09:30,820 --> 00:09:34,460
And she said to me one stage, why did you do this?

167
00:09:34,899 --> 00:09:36,000
I said, well, you know...

168
00:09:36,820 --> 00:09:39,779
People said you're putting Westfarmers at risk.

169
00:09:39,879 --> 00:09:41,120
I was never going to put Westfarmers at risk.

170
00:09:41,220 --> 00:09:44,620
I said, just put my job at risk for a period of time.

171
00:09:44,899 --> 00:09:45,940
We could handle that.

172
00:09:47,159 --> 00:09:52,299
I'm always interested in people who do great things over a sustained period of time.

173
00:09:52,940 --> 00:09:58,259
What daily routines and hacks to get through?

174
00:09:58,399 --> 00:10:00,759
I mean, you hear it's the AFL season launch.

175
00:10:00,860 --> 00:10:03,240
There's so many balls in the air in your world.

176
00:10:03,340 --> 00:10:06,519
What do you do day-to-day to keep you healthy and successful?

177
00:10:06,820 --> 00:10:09,799
I'm an incredibly supportive life partner.

178
00:10:11,379 --> 00:10:17,759
So, you know, Janine and I have been sort of great best friends almost since my first

179
00:10:17,759 --> 00:10:21,820
year of university and married for, I don't know, we're coming up 40 years soon.

180
00:10:22,059 --> 00:10:25,200
So that's been a great help for great kids.

181
00:10:25,200 --> 00:10:31,480
And so I think I've been able to have an appropriate balance of focusing on family

182
00:10:31,480 --> 00:10:35,019
and prioritising that at times.

183
00:10:35,500 --> 00:10:36,200
I've tried to...

184
00:10:36,820 --> 00:10:41,000
I've tried to remain reasonably fit because I don't think you're any good to anyone if

185
00:10:41,000 --> 00:10:42,919
you're not and if you're not healthy.

186
00:10:44,320 --> 00:10:46,000
And I've had pretty good mentors.

187
00:10:46,159 --> 00:10:51,100
I've had great mentors actually through my life who've from time to time corrected the

188
00:10:51,100 --> 00:10:55,919
course I was on, you know, when I was too focused on one thing and not focused on another.

189
00:10:56,740 --> 00:10:58,879
And a healthy...

190
00:10:58,879 --> 00:11:00,059
I'm not bad.

191
00:11:00,179 --> 00:11:02,220
I take my roles seriously.

192
00:11:02,340 --> 00:11:04,340
I try not to take myself too seriously, Luke.

193
00:11:05,379 --> 00:11:06,340
And so I...

194
00:11:06,820 --> 00:11:12,720
Hopefully people would say when they talk about me that I'm not high ego.

195
00:11:12,960 --> 00:11:19,000
I mean, I think if you want to be an ASX company CEO, you've got to have a degree of self-belief

196
00:11:19,000 --> 00:11:21,320
and so that implies ego.

197
00:11:21,320 --> 00:11:26,220
But hopefully people would say he's pretty balanced and he's relatively low ego.

198
00:11:26,720 --> 00:11:28,059
And I actually...

199
00:11:28,059 --> 00:11:30,620
I'm not worried about what people say about me.

200
00:11:30,679 --> 00:11:35,539
I worry a lot about what they say about the organisations I'm involved in and that probably.

201
00:11:36,820 --> 00:11:38,340
sort of helps me a bit as well.

202
00:11:38,460 --> 00:11:40,320
You mentioned some mentors along the way.

203
00:11:40,820 --> 00:11:43,360
Can you share a few names and their impact?

204
00:11:43,480 --> 00:11:44,100
Is that...

205
00:11:44,100 --> 00:11:46,179
I work for a guy, Michael Chaney at West Pharmacy.

206
00:11:46,220 --> 00:11:47,519
He's my predecessor's CEO.

207
00:11:47,940 --> 00:11:51,519
And Michael's been a friend and mentor for a long period of time.

208
00:11:51,919 --> 00:12:00,980
You know, really good values and some guidance early on in my career about just making the

209
00:12:00,980 --> 00:12:02,860
right call on ethics.

210
00:12:02,860 --> 00:12:05,279
Because on integrity, it's not...

211
00:12:05,279 --> 00:12:06,440
Luke, it's not black and white.

212
00:12:06,539 --> 00:12:06,659
You know...

213
00:12:06,820 --> 00:12:07,120
You know that.

214
00:12:08,320 --> 00:12:12,600
And I always say now to people, if it's a shade of grey, fall on the right side.

215
00:12:13,000 --> 00:12:13,399
Don't...

216
00:12:13,399 --> 00:12:15,700
And I think Michael was...

217
00:12:15,700 --> 00:12:16,879
Gave me great direction on that.

218
00:12:16,940 --> 00:12:19,259
I was very lucky through my time as CEO of West Pharmacy.

219
00:12:19,259 --> 00:12:23,220
I had a mentor, a guy called Chris Bartlett, who was a Harvard School professor.

220
00:12:24,279 --> 00:12:25,500
Chris grew up in Queensland.

221
00:12:25,740 --> 00:12:27,740
He was a King's Cup rower.

222
00:12:28,419 --> 00:12:29,679
He was a good rugby player.

223
00:12:30,019 --> 00:12:35,759
He was at McKinsey and Alcoa, I think, and ended up as a professor at Harvard Business School.

224
00:12:35,899 --> 00:12:36,539
And Chris and I would...

225
00:12:36,820 --> 00:12:40,799
We'd speak either face-to-face or on the phone every two weeks.

226
00:12:41,399 --> 00:12:42,840
And he was a true mentor.

227
00:12:43,059 --> 00:12:47,440
And he was the one person I could have the very, very blunt conversations with.

228
00:12:47,440 --> 00:12:49,639
And there were two-way conversations.

229
00:12:50,039 --> 00:12:54,860
And he would say things to me like, Richard, our last six calls, you've raised this as

230
00:12:54,860 --> 00:12:55,080
an issue.

231
00:12:55,159 --> 00:12:56,159
When are you going to do something about it?

232
00:12:56,159 --> 00:12:56,840
Sort of stuff, you know.

233
00:12:56,899 --> 00:13:04,039
So I had a person in Chris who was just an incredible sounding board through my time

234
00:13:04,039 --> 00:13:04,700
as CEO.

235
00:13:04,779 --> 00:13:06,740
Because leadership can be lonely, Luke.

236
00:13:07,240 --> 00:13:08,419
And everyone says it.

237
00:13:09,480 --> 00:13:12,539
And early on in my tenure as CEO of West Farmers, I thought, oh, no, it's not...

238
00:13:12,539 --> 00:13:13,240
You know, this is great.

239
00:13:13,379 --> 00:13:14,919
And then after a while, you think, oh, no.

240
00:13:15,700 --> 00:13:17,519
There are times when you are on your own.

241
00:13:18,080 --> 00:13:20,259
You know, people come in, you should do this, you should do that.

242
00:13:20,399 --> 00:13:21,779
And they close the door and walk out.

243
00:13:22,059 --> 00:13:24,840
And you've sort of got to think, well, what are we going to do?

244
00:13:25,139 --> 00:13:27,779
And so having a sounding board was great.

245
00:13:27,840 --> 00:13:32,340
And I talked earlier, Gail Kelly, she took over Westpac at a similar time I took over

246
00:13:32,340 --> 00:13:33,120
West Farmers.

247
00:13:33,120 --> 00:13:35,580
I always had a great relationship with Gail.

248
00:13:35,700 --> 00:13:36,120
You know, she's...

249
00:13:36,820 --> 00:13:43,620
Mother of triplets and a female major bank CEO in Australia was just, you know, I think

250
00:13:43,620 --> 00:13:44,539
is an incredible person.

251
00:13:44,820 --> 00:13:49,279
And so people like that, you can pick up the phone and talk to her, always really valuable.

252
00:13:49,440 --> 00:13:54,519
It sounds like you're smart enough to formalise that, you know, the Harvard business professor

253
00:13:54,519 --> 00:13:56,820
to make that something you did as a routine.

254
00:13:56,940 --> 00:13:58,919
Sounds like a really smart thing.

255
00:13:59,399 --> 00:14:03,799
Richard, if there's one criticism that you hear about you, it's maybe that you don't

256
00:14:03,799 --> 00:14:06,299
have a big public presence in the high profile.

257
00:14:06,519 --> 00:14:06,659
Chairman?

258
00:14:06,740 --> 00:14:06,799
Right?

259
00:14:06,799 --> 00:14:10,139
And it's hard to get access to you.

260
00:14:10,360 --> 00:14:15,620
And is that part because of, you know, the CEOs that you work with, Alan Joyce at Qantas

261
00:14:15,620 --> 00:14:20,899
and Gil McLaughlin at the AFL, Meg O'Neill at Woodside, you allow them, you empower them

262
00:14:20,899 --> 00:14:22,059
to do their job.

263
00:14:22,320 --> 00:14:26,519
Is that your natural style or have you sort of adapted it because, hey, I've got really

264
00:14:26,519 --> 00:14:29,379
capable people in those roles and I'm happy to take a back seat?

265
00:14:29,759 --> 00:14:31,080
It's a bit of both, Luke.

266
00:14:31,139 --> 00:14:33,639
So it's more my natural style.

267
00:14:33,639 --> 00:14:36,720
I mean, I hate opening a newspaper and seeing a photo.

268
00:14:36,799 --> 00:14:40,259
So maybe that's the farm boy bit in me.

269
00:14:40,940 --> 00:14:42,240
I don't know how you go with that.

270
00:14:44,879 --> 00:14:50,700
But I'm pretty clear on the difference between executive and non-executive roles.

271
00:14:51,659 --> 00:14:58,620
And so I had three great chairs when I was at West Farmers, Trevor Eastwood, Bob Avery

272
00:14:58,620 --> 00:14:59,720
and then Michael Chaney.

273
00:15:00,100 --> 00:15:06,019
And they gave me the scope to be the CEO, to be the face.

274
00:15:06,019 --> 00:15:08,139
That's when required of West Farmers.

275
00:15:08,879 --> 00:15:11,139
And they were supportive in the background.

276
00:15:11,379 --> 00:15:17,720
They were challenging when they needed to be, critical if they needed to be, but incredibly

277
00:15:17,720 --> 00:15:20,120
supportive and also focused on the long term.

278
00:15:20,200 --> 00:15:23,740
So I think I saw three very good role models as chair.

279
00:15:24,659 --> 00:15:27,940
And I'm, you know, I'm non-executive chair.

280
00:15:28,000 --> 00:15:28,720
I'm non-executive.

281
00:15:28,720 --> 00:15:30,220
And Gil runs the AFL.

282
00:15:30,679 --> 00:15:34,860
And the commission is, which is, I think, a brilliant structure.

283
00:15:35,039 --> 00:15:35,559
The commission.

284
00:15:36,019 --> 00:15:39,059
It looks at the strategies Gil and the team sets.

285
00:15:39,840 --> 00:15:41,500
We hire and fire the CEO.

286
00:15:42,379 --> 00:15:44,740
There's things we do as non-executives.

287
00:15:44,779 --> 00:15:46,679
But we don't run the AFL day to day.

288
00:15:46,720 --> 00:15:47,679
And I don't run Qantas.

289
00:15:48,279 --> 00:15:50,700
And although I get people ringing me up saying, where's my bag?

290
00:15:53,360 --> 00:15:57,240
And Alan Joyce is an enormously capable CEO, as is Gil.

291
00:15:57,740 --> 00:16:05,799
And one of the joys in my life for the last two years is seeing Meg O'Neill move into a leadership role at Woodside.

292
00:16:06,019 --> 00:16:07,639
And then blossom as a leader.

293
00:16:08,480 --> 00:16:11,960
And, you know, through her first time, we talked about Coles with me.

294
00:16:12,700 --> 00:16:18,480
Woodside merged with BHP Petroleum Assets last year, which was similar size, massive.

295
00:16:18,899 --> 00:16:20,940
You know, I think $16, $17, $18 billion.

296
00:16:21,220 --> 00:16:21,539
It doesn't matter.

297
00:16:21,720 --> 00:16:22,840
Big, big merger.

298
00:16:23,419 --> 00:16:25,940
And Meg led that very early on in her tenure.

299
00:16:25,940 --> 00:16:32,039
And I think she's already seen as a very, very, very highly capable CEO.

300
00:16:32,320 --> 00:16:35,940
She's got terrific relationships with government and industry.

301
00:16:36,559 --> 00:16:39,500
And it's been a joy for me to see her grow.

302
00:16:40,299 --> 00:16:41,379
And, look, there's a bit.

303
00:16:41,659 --> 00:16:42,419
I've had that.

304
00:16:42,559 --> 00:16:43,159
I've done that.

305
00:16:43,240 --> 00:16:46,460
And I don't seek the limelight.

306
00:16:46,580 --> 00:16:53,539
I seek the AFL to be as good as it can be, Qantas to be as good as it can be, and Woodside to be as good as it can be.

307
00:16:53,539 --> 00:16:55,940
And hopefully I can play a role in that.

308
00:16:56,220 --> 00:17:00,620
But I know that I'm not the day-to-day person running it.

309
00:17:00,759 --> 00:17:04,099
I know I get held accountable when we make mistakes.

310
00:17:04,619 --> 00:17:05,380
And that's fine.

311
00:17:06,019 --> 00:17:15,619
Richard, I want to talk about, you know, living in WA, you've come at a period of time where Western Australia was effectively cut off from the rest of the world for two years.

312
00:17:15,700 --> 00:17:21,799
And towards the end, you made some pretty strong statements around not being sustainable.

313
00:17:22,039 --> 00:17:27,099
If we look back, did we learn anything from the leadership in that time with a little bit of reflection there?

314
00:17:27,720 --> 00:17:29,579
Oh, look, I could talk all day about that.

315
00:17:30,480 --> 00:17:34,720
Actually, to its credit, the Western Australian Government's doing a review of its policies in COVID.

316
00:17:34,720 --> 00:17:35,839
And I hope.

317
00:17:36,019 --> 00:17:39,779
As a nation, we do a proper review of that.

318
00:17:40,240 --> 00:17:45,799
And so I'll be pretty blunt in my input to the Western Australian Government.

319
00:17:46,500 --> 00:17:53,019
I felt, yeah, I said a lot through those two or three years that leaders lead.

320
00:17:53,099 --> 00:17:58,000
I think Gil McLaughlin and Alan Joyce did phenomenal jobs through the most challenging period.

321
00:17:58,059 --> 00:17:59,059
They had great teams around them.

322
00:17:59,220 --> 00:18:00,319
And they'd be the first to say that.

323
00:18:00,319 --> 00:18:05,400
But for Qantas to survive COVID, for the AFL, frankly, to survive COVID.

324
00:18:06,019 --> 00:18:10,240
To give the delight to our supporters that we did was pretty amazing.

325
00:18:12,299 --> 00:18:20,400
I think we lost balance on risk management through COVID.

326
00:18:20,480 --> 00:18:23,460
And early on, it was really difficult because no one knew where it was going.

327
00:18:23,519 --> 00:18:32,460
But after a while, once a vaccine was developed and protocols were developed, it was, I think, far more manageable.

328
00:18:33,000 --> 00:18:35,599
I think there were people like Gladys Berejiklian.

329
00:18:36,019 --> 00:18:38,299
I absolutely canned by some people.

330
00:18:38,460 --> 00:18:45,279
And yet I'd look back and say that that was a better way of treating people.

331
00:18:45,460 --> 00:18:48,079
Because I reckon we just lost some of our humanity through COVID.

332
00:18:48,579 --> 00:18:50,579
And I think it was all based on one thing.

333
00:18:51,319 --> 00:18:57,859
And, look, if you took the same zero-risk approach that Western Australian Government apparently took

334
00:18:57,859 --> 00:19:00,599
or appeared to take through that period, no one would drive vehicles anymore.

335
00:19:01,119 --> 00:19:03,259
Or if we did, we'd drive at five kilometres per hour.

336
00:19:03,880 --> 00:19:05,359
And you wouldn't play football.

337
00:19:06,019 --> 00:19:07,700
Qantas would never fly an aeroplane.

338
00:19:08,279 --> 00:19:12,380
Because, you know, there's always a tiny – you know, you just minimise the risk.

339
00:19:12,960 --> 00:19:14,019
So I think we got that wrong.

340
00:19:14,079 --> 00:19:16,000
Hopefully we can get it sorted.

341
00:19:17,039 --> 00:19:19,880
You know, Australia was relatively better off than the rest of the world.

342
00:19:19,880 --> 00:19:25,859
I think we're lucky in a broad context with the leadership we had.

343
00:19:25,900 --> 00:19:28,200
I just think we lost a bit of humanity through that period.

344
00:19:28,400 --> 00:19:31,920
And we lost perspective on where it was all at.

345
00:19:32,220 --> 00:19:35,960
And I think it was really powerful to have senior people with influence like you,

346
00:19:36,019 --> 00:19:39,619
you know, question that narrative because, you know,

347
00:19:39,640 --> 00:19:41,559
it was an event that we hadn't experienced before.

348
00:19:41,799 --> 00:19:43,839
And I think your words are really profound.

349
00:19:43,980 --> 00:19:45,019
You know, we did lose humanity.

350
00:19:45,680 --> 00:19:48,240
It was a pretty rough couple of years around the world.

351
00:19:48,240 --> 00:19:52,119
But, you know, even here in Melbourne, we took kids out of school for two years.

352
00:19:52,319 --> 00:19:56,619
We, you know, I looked – you're lucky to live in an expansive house.

353
00:19:56,799 --> 00:20:00,500
I looked at people in the commission flats who couldn't get out with four or five –

354
00:20:00,500 --> 00:20:03,779
there was some cruelty that went on that's got lasting consequences.

355
00:20:03,779 --> 00:20:05,960
And if we don't have these conversations in leadership,

356
00:20:06,539 --> 00:20:07,859
how are you going to learn next time?

357
00:20:07,980 --> 00:20:08,400
Yeah, we need to.

358
00:20:08,500 --> 00:20:10,839
And we all – I mean, I've made plenty of mistakes, Luke.

359
00:20:10,859 --> 00:20:13,880
And we – I often thought about those people in the housing commission

360
00:20:13,880 --> 00:20:17,119
where English is second language and those kids miss two years of school.

361
00:20:17,480 --> 00:20:19,859
What's the impact going to be in 10 or 20 years' time?

362
00:20:20,200 --> 00:20:24,319
And we had – we had two children in Melbourne, a daughter here most of the time.

363
00:20:24,880 --> 00:20:30,339
And at one stage, you know, and she'd planned to get married, I think, in 21.

364
00:20:30,920 --> 00:20:33,759
In Perth, that got cancelled because borders got closed.

365
00:20:35,559 --> 00:20:35,839
And she – I don't know.

366
00:20:35,839 --> 00:20:35,960
I don't know.

367
00:20:35,960 --> 00:20:36,000
I don't know.

368
00:20:36,000 --> 00:20:36,019
I don't know.

369
00:20:36,019 --> 00:20:36,779
And she was lucky.

370
00:20:36,940 --> 00:20:41,019
She had a partner and the two of them were happy together.

371
00:20:41,160 --> 00:20:44,480
But her mental health suffered like many people in Victoria.

372
00:20:44,599 --> 00:20:47,539
And at one stage, I said to Janine, you might have to go to Melbourne.

373
00:20:47,619 --> 00:20:52,000
And I'm not sure when I'll see you again because you're not going to be allowed back to Perth.

374
00:20:52,039 --> 00:20:54,279
But you might have to go to look after our daughter.

375
00:20:55,259 --> 00:20:57,079
And they're cruel decisions.

376
00:20:57,420 --> 00:21:01,619
And, you know, there were people who weren't able to fly interstate to see dying relatives.

377
00:21:01,619 --> 00:21:06,000
There were people who weren't able to be in the same room as their husband

378
00:21:06,000 --> 00:21:09,740
or father or mother dying or weren't able to go and pick up bodies.

379
00:21:10,839 --> 00:21:12,460
And there was some crazy stuff.

380
00:21:12,660 --> 00:21:18,279
And hopefully, as you say, we can have a sensible conversation about how we do it better next time.

381
00:21:18,839 --> 00:21:23,859
I want to ask you about this sort of cancelled culture world we live in now.

382
00:21:23,960 --> 00:21:26,539
I love you saying openly you make mistakes.

383
00:21:26,640 --> 00:21:27,299
We all do.

384
00:21:27,700 --> 00:21:28,619
It's part of how you grow.

385
00:21:28,619 --> 00:21:32,680
Hopefully, you don't make them, you know, two in a row, particularly some of the big decisions you make.

386
00:21:32,799 --> 00:21:35,980
But we want to try and encourage – are you concerned, particularly in the –

387
00:21:35,980 --> 00:21:41,039
we like to attack Qantas and we like to attack the AFL

388
00:21:41,039 --> 00:21:47,259
and it doesn't seem to be that good-natured capacity to slip up occasionally.

389
00:21:47,680 --> 00:21:48,980
Excuse me, is that a concern for you?

390
00:21:49,200 --> 00:21:49,880
Yeah, it is.

391
00:21:50,740 --> 00:21:57,299
And you've put it well, Luke, because, I mean, there's more instant feedback on this stuff now.

392
00:21:57,299 --> 00:21:58,660
And it's quite personal.

393
00:21:59,960 --> 00:22:05,160
So I've actually pulled back from social media a bit because,

394
00:22:05,160 --> 00:22:10,759
it'd just kill you if you took seriously what people say about you.

395
00:22:10,920 --> 00:22:13,900
I don't know if you – where you're at on – because you'd get plenty of feedback as well.

396
00:22:13,900 --> 00:22:15,119
Well, I share this story, Richard.

397
00:22:15,200 --> 00:22:20,299
I'm sorry to jump in, but Luke Hodger, you know well, and he – I've told this story.

398
00:22:20,359 --> 00:22:21,380
He doesn't mind me telling it.

399
00:22:21,500 --> 00:22:25,119
One of the greats of our game, a Colac boy, not the similar background to you,

400
00:22:25,200 --> 00:22:27,220
but as iconic a leader as we've got in our game.

401
00:22:27,220 --> 00:22:32,160
I did one of the first games in commentary with Hodgie and second game he'd done it.

402
00:22:32,259 --> 00:22:35,140
So you're learning and you're nervous and at halftime,

403
00:22:35,160 --> 00:22:40,480
he went to check his phone to see how the kids were going and he scrolled onto social media

404
00:22:40,480 --> 00:22:45,420
and he showed me some of the stuff that – I'm going, if Luke Hodger's copying, you know,

405
00:22:45,480 --> 00:22:50,099
you are an idiot, you can't speak, you can't – I just was dumbfounded.

406
00:22:50,299 --> 00:22:51,619
And it knocked Luke Hodger out.

407
00:22:51,740 --> 00:22:53,079
It knocked him around in the second half.

408
00:22:53,140 --> 00:22:57,200
And I think, God, if someone with that level of resilience is susceptible,

409
00:22:57,839 --> 00:23:00,880
what are our teenage kids going to be able to cope with?

410
00:23:00,900 --> 00:23:01,559
It's crazy.

411
00:23:01,559 --> 00:23:05,140
Yeah, and in a high-profile role, it's like Gil McLaughlin.

412
00:23:05,240 --> 00:23:07,779
He at the AFL or Alan Joyce.

413
00:23:08,740 --> 00:23:13,059
I mean, Alan Joyce and his partner Shane bought a house in Sydney

414
00:23:13,059 --> 00:23:17,559
and it got eggs thrown at it and toilet paper and, you know, vandalised.

415
00:23:18,319 --> 00:23:21,799
Now, Alan's – at the end of the day, Alan is a great guy.

416
00:23:22,200 --> 00:23:24,400
He's been a superb leader of Qantas.

417
00:23:25,039 --> 00:23:26,259
Do we get everything right?

418
00:23:26,259 --> 00:23:32,460
No, but is Qantas as good as any airline in the world in my view?

419
00:23:32,700 --> 00:23:32,920
Yes.

420
00:23:33,039 --> 00:23:34,200
And did we get through COVID?

421
00:23:34,200 --> 00:23:36,460
We did amazingly well, yes.

422
00:23:37,240 --> 00:23:41,059
And I don't think we cut people any slack these days.

423
00:23:41,759 --> 00:23:44,599
And politically, you know, you'd ask the question,

424
00:23:44,700 --> 00:23:48,559
why would you be in politics these days given what they cop?

425
00:23:49,640 --> 00:23:52,140
I remember Gil saying to me one day, you know,

426
00:23:52,140 --> 00:23:55,500
even for the most popular decisions we make at the AFL,

427
00:23:55,579 --> 00:23:56,960
there's still people who hate it.

428
00:23:57,420 --> 00:23:59,119
And they express that hate.

429
00:24:01,319 --> 00:24:03,160
Look, it's really interesting.

430
00:24:03,160 --> 00:24:09,839
I think we've sort of got to get the balance slightly better

431
00:24:09,839 --> 00:24:12,160
than we've currently got at the moment.

432
00:24:12,500 --> 00:24:17,660
And so I've done a couple of speeches at graduation ceremonies

433
00:24:17,660 --> 00:24:19,579
at universities and things in recent years.

434
00:24:20,119 --> 00:24:22,000
And I say – I try and say it in a positive way.

435
00:24:22,000 --> 00:24:26,200
I say to these unbelievably well-educated kids who are going to be our leaders

436
00:24:26,200 --> 00:24:29,819
going forward, if you want to make change, make change.

437
00:24:30,200 --> 00:24:33,000
But having an opinion on social media is not –

438
00:24:33,000 --> 00:24:35,079
you're not the one making –

439
00:24:35,079 --> 00:24:39,279
you're far better off being the one criticised who's made the change

440
00:24:39,279 --> 00:24:43,539
than being some anonymous person on social media having a go.

441
00:24:44,019 --> 00:24:46,920
And in my view, that's what –

442
00:24:46,920 --> 00:24:50,299
we should be applauding the people who are actually doing stuff

443
00:24:50,299 --> 00:24:53,960
and recognising from time to time we get it wrong.

444
00:24:54,579 --> 00:24:57,240
You know, we were talking about West Farmers earlier and Coles

445
00:24:57,240 --> 00:24:58,099
and things like that.

446
00:24:58,299 --> 00:25:02,920
Look, if the West Farmers Board had acted like –

447
00:25:03,000 --> 00:25:05,099
social media does this way,

448
00:25:05,099 --> 00:25:09,619
I would have been fired 15 times in my 12-year tenure.

449
00:25:10,220 --> 00:25:13,640
But they took a view, which I'm forever grateful,

450
00:25:13,799 --> 00:25:15,220
that I'd learn from mistakes.

451
00:25:15,339 --> 00:25:17,680
I'd hopefully grow as a person and grow as a CEO.

452
00:25:18,259 --> 00:25:19,759
And they also took a long-term view.

453
00:25:20,039 --> 00:25:22,079
And they knew that we'd make mistakes from time to time.

454
00:25:22,140 --> 00:25:24,779
But hopefully, as you said earlier, we get more right than wrong.

455
00:25:25,460 --> 00:25:30,079
And you actually – you know, you come out – you're ahead of the game.

456
00:25:30,220 --> 00:25:30,839
You're a winner.

457
00:25:30,839 --> 00:25:30,900
You're a winner.

458
00:25:31,019 --> 00:25:31,839
But if –

459
00:25:33,000 --> 00:25:38,380
if I reacted to every time someone said I need to make a change at Qantas

460
00:25:38,380 --> 00:25:39,980
or, you know – everyone loves Gill, obviously.

461
00:25:40,119 --> 00:25:45,420
But, you know, I tell you, it would just be a –

462
00:25:45,420 --> 00:25:47,720
you know, we'd be rotating through people and things like that.

463
00:25:47,740 --> 00:25:49,680
So we've got to – I think we've got to get better at it.

464
00:25:49,680 --> 00:25:53,400
And I'm going to be – I'm now 63, Luke.

465
00:25:55,140 --> 00:25:57,700
You know, I've got a Woodside AGM coming up soon.

466
00:25:58,200 --> 00:25:59,900
I'm going to have people coming along with the AGM

467
00:26:00,240 --> 00:26:02,140
saying you're not doing enough on climate change.

468
00:26:02,140 --> 00:26:05,299
There's – there'll be some who are legitimate,

469
00:26:06,519 --> 00:26:08,200
will have a very good, healthy debate.

470
00:26:08,279 --> 00:26:09,839
There's some who just don't want us to be in business.

471
00:26:11,420 --> 00:26:14,339
My response to that is fine, but that's not my job.

472
00:26:14,420 --> 00:26:18,259
My job's not actually to – my job's actually to make Woodside as good as it can be.

473
00:26:18,319 --> 00:26:18,519
Yeah.

474
00:26:18,660 --> 00:26:20,259
And your agenda is to get us out of this business.

475
00:26:22,200 --> 00:26:23,259
There's no point in us talking.

476
00:26:23,740 --> 00:26:24,740
