00:32:04,559 --> 00:32:07,579
And we think it's hard to lead anyone else unless you have a sense

599
00:32:07,579 --> 00:32:08,640
of self-leadership.

600
00:32:09,119 --> 00:32:10,140
Does that resonate with you?

601
00:32:10,319 --> 00:32:11,259
Yeah, yeah, it does.

602
00:32:11,700 --> 00:32:13,779
And I think that goes to your values.

603
00:32:14,039 --> 00:32:17,700
It goes to your own sort of compass, personal compass.

604
00:32:19,220 --> 00:32:22,079
And I've always said if you're not prepared to do it yourself,

605
00:32:22,180 --> 00:32:24,259
you certainly can't ask anyone else to do it.

606
00:32:24,480 --> 00:32:26,000
So, yeah, it does resonate, yeah.

607
00:32:26,000 --> 00:32:29,099
We think our leaders are really, modern leaders are really conscious

608
00:32:29,099 --> 00:32:30,099
about every moment.

609
00:32:30,359 --> 00:32:32,900
And having a positive impact on whatever environment they're in,

610
00:32:33,039 --> 00:32:34,559
is that something you think of?

611
00:32:35,319 --> 00:32:38,079
Yeah, it's interesting.

612
00:32:38,339 --> 00:32:42,519
One of the things I've always tried to do, Luke, is be positive

613
00:32:42,519 --> 00:32:45,240
even when things were terribly difficult.

614
00:32:46,039 --> 00:32:47,359
And sometimes they are.

615
00:32:49,500 --> 00:32:55,180
And there was a, you know, when I was looking to retire

616
00:32:55,180 --> 00:32:59,299
as CEO of West Farmers, there were some internal candidates.

617
00:33:00,359 --> 00:33:06,099
And one of the internal candidates and I had a terrific conversation

618
00:33:06,099 --> 00:33:08,599
and this person is someone I really admire and respect.

619
00:33:10,200 --> 00:33:16,160
But there were times when that person was not able to put a front on,

620
00:33:16,259 --> 00:33:18,640
which is actually we're going to work this through,

621
00:33:18,700 --> 00:33:19,359
we're going to be positive.

622
00:33:20,180 --> 00:33:24,900
And you can't have a leader come into a place like the AFL or whatever

623
00:33:24,900 --> 00:33:29,220
just like the world's going to fall over because that impacts everyone.

624
00:33:29,339 --> 00:33:30,200
So I think you've got...

625
00:33:30,200 --> 00:33:36,039
You can't internalise all the issues because if you do,

626
00:33:36,099 --> 00:33:36,839
you're not going to solve them.

627
00:33:36,920 --> 00:33:41,039
The best way of solving issues is to make sure your team's aware of them

628
00:33:41,039 --> 00:33:42,259
and you're bored or whatever.

629
00:33:43,839 --> 00:33:46,259
But I think as a leader, you have to have a positive.

630
00:33:46,259 --> 00:33:48,980
You have to be able to say, we're going to work our way through this.

631
00:33:49,420 --> 00:33:51,079
It might take us a bit of time and it might be hard,

632
00:33:51,140 --> 00:33:52,539
but we're going to work our way through it.

633
00:33:52,559 --> 00:33:56,259
And that's why Gil's leadership through COVID

634
00:33:56,839 --> 00:34:00,180
and Alan Joyce's leadership through COVID was so powerful.

635
00:34:00,200 --> 00:34:03,160
I think because Alan said,

636
00:34:03,579 --> 00:34:06,619
Qantas was six weeks away from insolvency basically,

637
00:34:06,799 --> 00:34:10,059
but tough decisions, really tough decisions,

638
00:34:10,219 --> 00:34:14,380
but people respecting that because there was an optimism

639
00:34:14,380 --> 00:34:15,579
that we'd get through it.

640
00:34:16,360 --> 00:34:19,980
And jumping off on this topic, I hadn't planned to do it,

