00:38:09,900 --> 00:38:17,179
I love being chair because I think you've got more influence as a chair,

723
00:38:17,699 --> 00:38:20,940
obviously, than you do purely as a non-executive.

724
00:38:21,300 --> 00:38:27,059
And so in my view, the vision of the AFL is something for Gil

725
00:38:27,059 --> 00:38:29,159
and the team to come up with.

726
00:38:29,599 --> 00:38:36,079
For the commission to critique and hopefully critique maybe help make better

727
00:38:36,079 --> 00:38:38,139
but then come behind and support.

728
00:38:38,239 --> 00:38:42,400
And the same with, you know, listed companies and the like.

729
00:38:43,500 --> 00:38:48,280
I think, though, having clarity of direction is incredibly important, Luke.

730
00:38:48,300 --> 00:38:52,699
And as a leader, one of the reasons I said Michael Chaney was a great mentor

731
00:38:52,699 --> 00:38:56,739
was I was always very clear with what Michael wanted from me

732
00:38:56,739 --> 00:38:58,119
as someone working for him.

733
00:38:58,719 --> 00:38:59,579
So hopefully the people...

734
00:38:59,579 --> 00:39:05,400
The people who work for me, either as executives when I was a CEO

735
00:39:05,400 --> 00:39:09,340
or now as CEOs, are really clear.

736
00:39:09,739 --> 00:39:13,519
And the first thing is integrity is non-negotiable.

737
00:39:13,820 --> 00:39:16,480
You know, we're not compromised on that.

738
00:39:17,099 --> 00:39:22,639
If you're a listed company, then it's pretty clear that you're looking

739
00:39:22,639 --> 00:39:25,739
to create value for your stakeholders, including your shareholders.

740
00:39:26,019 --> 00:39:29,500
And for the AFL, you know, we have a vision that we all jump

741
00:39:29,500 --> 00:39:31,619
in behind and you and I, the way...

742
00:39:31,619 --> 00:39:34,940
The conversation we've just had basically goes to that vision

743
00:39:34,940 --> 00:39:39,219
about how we make the game better and inclusive for all Australians.

744
00:39:39,920 --> 00:39:40,519
So...

745
00:39:40,519 --> 00:39:43,940
But that clarity...

746
00:39:44,719 --> 00:39:47,460
So you have to be clear in your own mind about where you're going, I think,

747
00:39:47,500 --> 00:39:51,900
and then being clear, making sure that others are clear are important.

748
00:39:52,219 --> 00:39:57,719
And the bit on integrity is, I think, really important.

749
00:39:57,860 --> 00:39:58,980
Holding people accountable.

750
00:39:59,500 --> 00:40:03,420
I think that's really important for results, good and bad.

751
00:40:03,420 --> 00:40:07,820
But as I think I said earlier, I don't worry what people say about me.

752
00:40:07,820 --> 00:40:10,420
Although if they question my integrity, I'd worry about that.

753
00:40:10,599 --> 00:40:14,059
But I do worry about what they say about the organisations.

754
00:40:14,059 --> 00:40:20,420
And I hate the integrity of organisations I'm involved in to be attacked.

755
00:40:20,420 --> 00:40:24,900
And so they're things that, to me, become not negotiable.

756
00:40:25,280 --> 00:40:28,139
And I think I heard you in a very similar vein, just saying we're going

757
00:40:28,139 --> 00:40:29,219
to have lots of debates.

758
00:40:29,219 --> 00:40:29,480
And...

759
00:40:29,500 --> 00:40:33,539
And lots of blues, and you can disagree, but integrity stands alone.

760
00:40:33,719 --> 00:40:36,480
And a question on that, that's a separate conversation.

761
00:40:36,880 --> 00:40:38,340
And, yeah, it makes sense, yeah.

762
00:40:38,460 --> 00:40:41,280
And it's one of the interesting dynamics about, I think,

763
00:40:41,300 --> 00:40:47,559
a management team, Luke, and a board, is you actually want lively debate.

764
00:40:47,699 --> 00:40:49,659
You want diversity of views around a table.

765
00:40:50,699 --> 00:40:52,820
Because you'll get better outcomes with it.

766
00:40:53,139 --> 00:40:57,519
But when you leave, you've got to have a unified voice.

767
00:40:57,920 --> 00:40:59,219
And if you don't...

768
00:40:59,219 --> 00:41:02,320
If people play politics, that can be very destructive in an organisation.

769
00:41:02,320 --> 00:41:08,579
And so I think how you manage boards around confidentiality,

770
00:41:08,739 --> 00:41:12,940
but having that openness, and your own management teams as well,

771
00:41:13,000 --> 00:41:14,320
I think becomes really important.

772
00:41:15,039 --> 00:41:17,940
And, you know, there should be a diversity of views,

773
00:41:18,679 --> 00:41:20,199
but eventually you should come to a landing.

774
00:41:20,440 --> 00:41:21,320
And once you've come to a landing...

775
00:41:22,260 --> 00:41:25,179
And if you can't live with that, go and do something.

776
00:41:25,179 --> 00:41:25,820
Then you're out.

777
00:41:25,900 --> 00:41:26,440
Then you're out.

778
00:41:26,440 --> 00:41:26,980
Go and do something else.

779
00:41:27,219 --> 00:41:28,780
So I'm bored.

780
00:41:29,219 --> 00:41:32,360
Even if you disagree, eventually you have to come to a united front.

781
00:41:32,579 --> 00:41:34,920
And without that, there's no harmony, yeah.

782
00:41:35,239 --> 00:41:37,800
And one of the challenges of being a chair or a CEO

783
00:41:37,800 --> 00:41:43,699
is getting to that position without compromising on every front.

784
00:41:43,820 --> 00:41:45,039
Because sometimes you think,

785
00:41:45,179 --> 00:41:47,340
geez, do we actually make a decision here or not?

786
00:41:47,679 --> 00:41:49,280
So anyway, it's one of the challenges.

787
00:41:50,139 --> 00:41:53,599
Richard, we see leaders are really curious people.

788
00:41:53,599 --> 00:41:57,980
And curiosity is a way that they launch into their own self-improvement and development.

789
00:41:58,099 --> 00:41:59,199
Does that word resonate?

790
00:41:59,219 --> 00:42:00,099
Does that resonate with you, curiosity?

791
00:42:01,679 --> 00:42:04,019
Curiosity, yeah, you know, sort of deep scanning.

792
00:42:04,159 --> 00:42:10,599
I can't help myself but be looking at what's going on around the place,

793
00:42:10,739 --> 00:42:14,539
whether that's economically, whether that's politically, whether the whole...

794
00:42:14,539 --> 00:42:17,139
So I'm curious.

795
00:42:17,260 --> 00:42:18,500
I have a view on a lot of things.

796
00:42:18,900 --> 00:42:20,500
I have to hold myself back sometimes.

797
00:42:22,619 --> 00:42:25,780
I've made the mistake plenty of times in my life thinking I'm right

798
00:42:25,780 --> 00:42:28,260
and something worked out that I wasn't.

799
00:42:29,219 --> 00:42:31,460
And that's why it's really good to have people around you

800
00:42:31,460 --> 00:42:34,539
who can have a different view.

801
00:42:34,659 --> 00:42:39,099
But yeah, I think the world's in a really interesting place at the moment.

802
00:42:39,099 --> 00:42:42,460
I've got four kids, first grandchild now.

803
00:42:43,320 --> 00:42:49,099
So I want the world to be a good place for them to be in.

804
00:42:49,940 --> 00:42:51,960
And so I'm really interested in stuff.

805
00:42:52,079 --> 00:42:54,659
Sometimes I think, no, let it go, let others deal with it,

806
00:42:54,719 --> 00:42:58,460
and I'll go up to the farm and run around the sheep or something.

807
00:42:58,559 --> 00:42:59,079
But there's others.

808
00:42:59,079 --> 00:43:00,099
I just can't help myself.

809
00:43:00,300 --> 00:43:02,199
And I have to pick up the phone and ring someone and say,

810
00:43:02,360 --> 00:43:04,760
are they serious about this?

811
00:43:04,780 --> 00:43:05,280
Are we doing this?

812
00:43:05,679 --> 00:43:07,300
So yeah, I'm...

813
00:43:07,300 --> 00:43:09,739
So you hold yourself back on purpose, do you?

814
00:43:09,860 --> 00:43:09,960
Sometimes.

815
00:43:10,139 --> 00:43:12,340
Yeah, because you just think it's not worth it or...?

816
00:43:12,340 --> 00:43:15,039
Yeah, sometimes because I think actually they don't know.

817
00:43:15,159 --> 00:43:16,800
Someone doesn't need to hear from me on this.

818
00:43:17,460 --> 00:43:20,440
So yeah, I'm probably a bit better than I was five or ten years ago.

819
00:43:20,860 --> 00:43:22,500
But have you picked up the phone and thought,

820
00:43:22,500 --> 00:43:25,780
you know, I can probably reach people that others can't?

821
00:43:26,039 --> 00:43:28,719
And have you done that from time to time as well on an issue?

822
00:43:29,079 --> 00:43:30,579
That you care about?

823
00:43:30,820 --> 00:43:31,539
Yeah, I have.

824
00:43:31,659 --> 00:43:33,480
And hopefully I don't abuse that.

825
00:43:33,539 --> 00:43:36,840
So hopefully people respect it.

826
00:43:38,000 --> 00:43:43,320
Yeah, and I'm lucky and I've got a really good network of contacts

827
00:43:43,320 --> 00:43:45,719
and I've got people who reach out to me from time to time as well.

828
00:43:45,820 --> 00:43:46,860
So that's fine.

829
00:43:47,559 --> 00:43:53,800
But one of the key things is I listen to my kids a lot.

830
00:43:54,420 --> 00:43:56,800
You know, they're great kids.

831
00:43:59,079 --> 00:44:01,619
And I think sometimes you've got to make sure you look in the mirror

832
00:44:01,619 --> 00:44:02,980
and say, who are you?

833
00:44:03,719 --> 00:44:07,579
And do you really understand some of the stuff that's going on

834
00:44:07,579 --> 00:44:08,280
and that's important?

835
00:44:08,719 --> 00:44:09,800
So, yeah.

836
00:44:10,280 --> 00:44:11,900
Which is a great parenting skill, isn't it?

837
00:44:11,920 --> 00:44:14,860
As you get all your great teachers are there right in front of you.

838
00:44:15,239 --> 00:44:18,019
I know I get plenty of feedback from my floor as well, Richard,

839
00:44:18,099 --> 00:44:18,980
whether I like it or not.

840
00:44:20,219 --> 00:44:22,199
Communicating with clarity is another dimension of leadership.

841
00:44:22,360 --> 00:44:26,719
We see people in roles like yours are very clear on their communication.

842
00:44:27,159 --> 00:44:28,300
How have you gone about that?

843
00:44:29,079 --> 00:44:34,920
Well, yeah, I think I've, you know, there's been a journey, Luke.

844
00:44:34,920 --> 00:44:38,719
I've learned to be a bit more direct with people without,

845
00:44:38,900 --> 00:44:42,059
hopefully without being sort of rude and impolite.

846
00:44:43,480 --> 00:44:49,460
But so I can have very direct conversations with people with, you know,

847
00:44:49,480 --> 00:44:58,039
whether it's Alan or Gil or Meg or directors because I think that clarity

848
00:44:58,039 --> 00:44:58,900
is important.

849
00:44:59,079 --> 00:45:02,139
And do I enjoy sitting down with someone and say,

850
00:45:02,239 --> 00:45:04,000
I think you did a really rubbish job?

851
00:45:04,139 --> 00:45:04,380
No.

852
00:45:05,159 --> 00:45:07,099
You know, I don't know who enjoys that stuff.

853
00:45:07,099 --> 00:45:11,420
But have I learned to sit down and say, actually, you know,

854
00:45:11,579 --> 00:45:14,579
you could have done that better and these are what I think you should have done.

855
00:45:14,900 --> 00:45:18,639
I think I'm a lot better at that now than I was 20 years ago.

856
00:45:19,099 --> 00:45:22,440
And it's a skill I think you sort of have to develop.

857
00:45:24,139 --> 00:45:28,099
But also, you know, I've also, I've had feedback along the way that people

858
00:45:29,079 --> 00:45:31,599
felt they weren't getting enough feedback from me.

859
00:45:31,659 --> 00:45:33,840
And I was shocked when I got that feedback.

860
00:45:33,840 --> 00:45:35,280
I thought, oh, gee, I'm pretty good at that.

861
00:45:35,320 --> 00:45:37,260
And then I reflected on it and said, actually, no, I'm not.

862
00:45:37,340 --> 00:45:40,460
I'm bloody hopeless at it in the circumstances I was talking about.

863
00:45:40,900 --> 00:45:43,380
So, yeah, hopefully I'm a bit better.

864
00:45:43,519 --> 00:45:45,400
It also comes with relationships, I think.

865
00:45:45,539 --> 00:45:51,739
Once you build trust with someone, you can have that much more direct conversation.

866
00:45:52,699 --> 00:45:55,739
Well, you really see that shift to collaboration.

867
00:45:56,059 --> 00:45:58,800
How important has collaboration been for you?

868
00:45:58,800 --> 00:45:59,539
As a leader?

869
00:46:00,500 --> 00:46:04,539
Well, there's nothing better, I think, as a leadership team

870
00:46:04,539 --> 00:46:07,739
in agreeing something and then making it happen.

871
00:46:09,019 --> 00:46:12,619
Early on in my schoolboy life, I rode.

872
00:46:13,139 --> 00:46:14,079
I wasn't a great rower.

873
00:46:14,139 --> 00:46:15,639
My brother was a much better rower than me.

874
00:46:15,699 --> 00:46:18,500
But I rode because I got better food at the boarding school.

875
00:46:19,400 --> 00:46:23,300
But those moments in an eight when everything comes together,

876
00:46:23,599 --> 00:46:24,639
I don't know if you ever rode,

877
00:46:24,639 --> 00:46:28,500
but those moments when everything clicks and you're at one,

878
00:46:28,800 --> 00:46:31,320
is one of those magic, magic moments.

879
00:46:31,400 --> 00:46:34,480
I keep sort of thinking about that sometimes in corporate life.

880
00:46:34,599 --> 00:46:41,460
So the best times in my corporate life were in an office with a whole team

881
00:46:41,460 --> 00:46:45,619
working on a difficult issue, whether it was an acquisition

882
00:46:45,619 --> 00:46:49,539
or just a challenge in the business and working our way through it

883
00:46:49,539 --> 00:46:52,219
and coming out, that is so good.

884
00:46:52,219 --> 00:46:58,300
And particularly when the best ideas come from the most unlikely source.

885
00:46:58,800 --> 00:47:01,579
And I love that sort of stuff.

886
00:47:01,840 --> 00:47:04,280
I love that sort of teamwork, collaboration.

887
00:47:05,440 --> 00:47:06,000
Yeah, it's great.

888
00:47:06,239 --> 00:47:08,199
Yeah, and I love hearing you say that.

889
00:47:08,320 --> 00:47:11,800
The rowing analogy, I didn't know nothing about,

890
00:47:11,880 --> 00:47:15,579
but my daughter, I've had this great joy of watching her.

891
00:47:15,659 --> 00:47:17,639
I have a proud dad moment here for a moment, Richard,

892
00:47:17,719 --> 00:47:19,940
but they competed over in Henley last year.

893
00:47:20,280 --> 00:47:22,800
And it's the ultimate team sport, isn't it?

894
00:47:22,800 --> 00:47:27,320
In an eight, they had this incredible success and won over in Henley.

895
00:47:27,440 --> 00:47:27,780
And you're thinking,

896
00:47:27,780 --> 00:47:32,579
one person puts that oar in the wrong spot once, and it's unlikely.

897
00:47:33,039 --> 00:47:34,280
And you look at the crew and you think,

898
00:47:34,440 --> 00:47:36,880
God, that doesn't look like they should go fast.

899
00:47:36,900 --> 00:47:39,519
But sometimes when it works, there's magic in it, isn't it?

900
00:47:39,639 --> 00:47:44,219
And you actually know when you're in a crew, you can see the puddles.

901
00:47:45,000 --> 00:47:47,159
So you know who's working and you know who's not.

902
00:47:47,820 --> 00:47:48,500
You can.

903
00:47:50,139 --> 00:47:51,519
And we've all been there.

904
00:47:51,559 --> 00:47:53,659
We've all been not on our game.

905
00:47:53,800 --> 00:47:54,079
Yeah.

906
00:47:54,280 --> 00:47:55,860
And you know, yeah.

907
00:47:55,860 --> 00:47:57,440
And you know when you're not on your game.

908
00:47:57,780 --> 00:48:01,019
But when it all clicks, it's pretty magic.

909
00:48:01,340 --> 00:48:01,719
Yeah.

910
00:48:01,920 --> 00:48:05,360
I can't help it, you know, that poor Olympic moment,

911
00:48:05,579 --> 00:48:07,920
which we'll never forget, and I shouldn't bring it up,

912
00:48:07,920 --> 00:48:11,639
but thinking of the Olympic final in a team situation like that,

913
00:48:11,719 --> 00:48:14,760
where clearly you couldn't go on.

914
00:48:15,039 --> 00:48:19,079
But, you know, that would stay with you for a long time, I'm assuming.

915
00:48:19,500 --> 00:48:20,539
Two final questions.

916
00:48:21,239 --> 00:48:22,980
Richard, who's been the greatest leader in your life?

917
00:48:24,579 --> 00:48:26,920
Oh, I think Mandela's the –

918
00:48:27,780 --> 00:48:32,340
you know, and I think he's –

919
00:48:32,340 --> 00:48:36,360
what he did, what he went through, his humility,

920
00:48:37,239 --> 00:48:41,780
his clarity when, you know, after years of being locked up.

921
00:48:42,760 --> 00:48:47,699
I was lucky enough to see him at Harvard back in 98 when I was over there,

922
00:48:47,760 --> 00:48:51,119
and it was one of those literally spine-chilling moments,

923
00:48:51,119 --> 00:48:54,739
and it was with a whole bunch of other students at Harvard.

924
00:48:55,699 --> 00:48:57,480
Did he come and do a guest lecture?

925
00:48:57,780 --> 00:49:02,159
He was given an award, which I think only previously had been given to Churchill

926
00:49:02,159 --> 00:49:05,039
and one other – it might have been FDA –

927
00:49:05,039 --> 00:49:09,000
one other – so the third time ever that this award had been given.

928
00:49:09,500 --> 00:49:12,820
And it was at Harvard Square, and, you know, I was –

929
00:49:12,820 --> 00:49:17,739
at the time in 98, I was, what, 38, but there's all these Harvard students,

930
00:49:17,739 --> 00:49:24,960
and it was just unbelievable to be sort of in the distance, but in his presence.

931
00:49:25,119 --> 00:49:27,739
I just think as a leader, he –

932
00:49:27,780 --> 00:49:31,699
he exhibited the things that you'd want to see, as I said,

933
00:49:32,179 --> 00:49:35,519
humility, grace, direction, compassion.

934
00:49:36,539 --> 00:49:36,940
Amazing.

935
00:49:37,199 --> 00:49:37,460
Yeah.

936
00:49:37,579 --> 00:49:40,760
I think we're about to get wound up in the Brownlow room here at the AFL.

937
00:49:41,300 --> 00:49:42,539
I think our meeting's about to expire.

938
00:49:42,599 --> 00:49:43,400
One final question.

939
00:49:43,559 --> 00:49:45,000
It's handy when you've got the chairman here.

940
00:49:45,119 --> 00:49:49,519
I'll get my final question away before we get to –

941
00:49:49,519 --> 00:49:52,840
in the spirit of collaboration, I love – you know, I read out the start.

942
00:49:52,840 --> 00:49:57,079
You're raising money for juvenile diabetes research.

943
00:49:57,780 --> 00:50:00,599
The Western Australian Telethon is iconic in what it's done.

944
00:50:01,639 --> 00:50:02,559
All your passions.

945
00:50:02,699 --> 00:50:06,260
If you could collaborate with anyone, maybe Mandela might be the answer.

946
00:50:06,280 --> 00:50:08,099
Is there anyone that you thought, if I could collaborate with someone,

947
00:50:08,179 --> 00:50:08,679
that would be it?

948
00:50:10,320 --> 00:50:16,800
Like, such a – you know, I love doing the work here with Gil and the team

949
00:50:16,800 --> 00:50:17,880
and in other places.

950
00:50:18,940 --> 00:50:27,420
I'm a massive admirer of Barack Obama, and I met him at the time of the Australian G20

951
00:50:27,420 --> 00:50:27,760
in –

952
00:50:27,780 --> 00:50:29,699
in 2014 when I was running the B20.

953
00:50:30,840 --> 00:50:34,179
And he's a farm boy from Tambalup sitting next to him

954
00:50:34,179 --> 00:50:36,000
and having a conversation with the President of the United States,

955
00:50:36,059 --> 00:50:38,199
which was pretty surreal for me.

956
00:50:39,139 --> 00:50:44,420
And I had a genuinely good conversation with him.

957
00:50:44,980 --> 00:50:48,480
And he invited me to the White House, but, you know, subsequently,

958
00:50:48,739 --> 00:50:51,400
there's no way he can get through all those bloody protocols.

959
00:50:51,760 --> 00:50:55,219
But I'd love – I'd love to work with him on something

960
00:50:55,219 --> 00:50:57,219
because I just think he's an outstanding person.

961
00:50:57,780 --> 00:51:00,900
You know, not without his faults, and I've read his books.

962
00:51:00,980 --> 00:51:01,820
I don't know if you've read his books.

963
00:51:02,119 --> 00:51:05,059
And, yeah, he – but I'd love to do something with him

